,"England":"England","Paulerspury, Northamptonshire, England":"Paulerspury, Northamptonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Paveley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Pawley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Pavelin","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Paveley   (  see  Pawley  ) with an excrescent  <i>-n</i>."]},{"name":"Pawley","meanings":["English: variant of   Pauley  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":16,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705188,"age":25,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Paveley IV was born in 1199, in England, his father, Geoffrey De Paveley, was 34 and his mother, Mrs. Matilda Paveley, was 22. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Petronilla Paveley. He died in 1250, in his hometown, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1199–1250":"1199–1250","1192–1245":"1192–1245","1220–1288":"1220–1288","1166–Male":"1166–Surnud","1177–Female":"1177–Surnud","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","1288":"1288","1199":"1199","1177":"1177","1166":"1166","1220":"1220","1250":"1250","about 1220":"umbes 1220","1192":"1192","England":"England","Paulerspury, Northamptonshire, England":"Paulerspury, Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"1199–1250":"1199–1250","1192–1245":"1192–1245","1220–1288":"1220–1288","1166–Male":"1166–Kuollut","1177–Female":"1177–Kuollut","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","1288":"1288","1199":"1199","1177":"1177","1166":"1166","1220":"1220","1250":"1250","about 1220":"noin 1220","1192":"1192","England":"England","Paulerspury, Northamptonshire, England":"Paulerspury, Northamptonshire, England"},"fr":{"1199–1250":"1199–1250","1192–1245":"1192–1245","1220–1288":"1220–1288","1166–Male":"1166–Décédé","1177–Female":"1177–Décédée","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","1288":"1288","1199":"1199","1177":"1177","1166":"1166","1220":"1220","1250":"1250","about 1220":"environ 1220","1192":"1192","England":"Angleterre","Paulerspury, Northamptonshire, England":"Paulerspury, Northamptonshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Robert Paveley IV est né en 1199, à Angleterre, son père, Geoffrey De Paveley, avait 34 ans et sa mère, Mrs. Matilda Paveley, avait 22 ans. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Mrs. Petr